<p>Guidelines about company-specific terminology.</p>

<h2 id="branding">Branding</h2>

<h3 id="product-names">Product names<br /></h3>
<p>Our product offerings include <strong>MediaGuard</strong>, <strong>FraudSensor</strong>, <strong>BotGuard for Growth Marketing</strong>, <strong>Botguard for Applications</strong>, and <strong>the HUMAN Mobile SDK</strong>.</p>

<p>Don’t shorten Aperture Science’s product names in public-facing documentation.<br /></p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p><strong>No:</strong> BGforA protects your website or application from bots.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Yes:</strong> BotGuard for Applications protects your website or application from bots.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

<h2 id="other-terminology">Other terminology</h2>

<h3 id="words-to-avoid">Words to avoid<br /></h3>
<ul>
  <li>Don’t refer to test subjects as <em>guinea pigs</em> or <em>lab rats</em>. Instead, be sure to reassure all test subjects that they are active participants in the scientific process and possess far greater cognitive faculties than your average rodent.</li>
  <li>Don’t use words like <em>experiment</em> or <em>unaccredited clinical trial</em>; instead, say <em>test</em> or <em>Aperture Science Data Collection Session</em>.</li>
</ul>

